### Step 3 — Deploy the SAML Service Provider (SimpleSAMLphp)

On your Ubuntu VM, run the SP setup script. Installs Apache, PHP, SimpleSAMLphp, generates SP key pair, and wires up the IdP metadata.

```bash
# First download the IdP signing cert:
# Entra ID → Enterprise Apps → IAM-SSO-MFA-Lab → SAML → Certificates → Download (Base64)

sudo bash scripts/bash/setup-simplesamlphp-sp.sh \
    "https://sts.windows.net/your-tenant-id/" \
    "https://login.microsoftonline.com/your-tenant-id/saml2" \
    "./idp-signing.crt" \
    "sp.lab.local"
```

After the script completes, take the SP Entity ID and ACS URL from the output and register them back in the Azure AD SAML config (Identifier and Reply URL fields).

**SimpleSAMLphp SP — configuration verified, lab-sp auth source ready:**

-----

### Step 4 — Trigger SSO and Satisfy MFA

1. Browse to `https://sp.lab.local/simplesaml`
1. Click **Test configured authentication sources → lab-sp**
1. You’re redirected to Azure AD — authenticate with your credentials
1. Conditional Access evaluates → MFA challenge fires

**Azure AD MFA prompt — triggered by Conditional Access policy:**

1. Approve the push notification or enter your TOTP code
1. Azure AD issues a signed SAML assertion with `amr=["mfa","pwd","otp"]`
1. You’re redirected back to the SP with the decoded assertion

**SimpleSAMLphp — SSO success, attributes received, amr=mfa confirmed:**

-----

### Step 5 — Inspect the SAML Assertion

The SimpleSAMLphp test page decodes the full assertion. Key fields to verify:

|Claim                 |Expected Value                     |What It Means         |
|----------------------|-----------------------------------|----------------------|
|`amr`                 |`["mfa", "pwd", "otp"]`            |MFA was satisfied     |
|`AuthnContextClassRef`|`PasswordProtectedTransport`       |Auth context          |
|Signature             |Valid (IdP cert thumbprint matches)|Assertion not tampered|
|`NotOnOrAfter`        |Future timestamp                   |Assertion not expired |

